40|$|The {{crisis of}} 1931 {{was a world}} crisis. The nations of the world, {{just as much as}} they lacked the desire and the {{capacity}} for united political action, lacked the economic techniques and the financial and fiscal apparatus which could have dealt with the fierce and corrosive maladies by which they were beset. The events of 1931 were tragic in themselves, but they were the first act of a far more massive and all-embracing tragedy, whose completion was to take many years. For Britain the crisis was severe and protracted; both in her political life and in her economy she was affected externally and internally, by industrial depression and the growing dangers of military aggression. On September 18, 1931, Japanese troops in Manchuria occupied Mukden on the pretext that the railway had been cut: probably they had done ita themseleves. In any case it was the occasion, not the cause, of the seizure of Manchuria, for which elaborate preparations had been made. Japan had broken the Covenant, the Washington Nine-Power Treaty, and the Pact of Paris; the National Government of Britain, formed in the autumn of 1931, played for safety. Great Britain held the key position at Geneva. As she was the strongest naval power in the League, no sanvtionary action, whether economic or military, could be of any effect without her full participation. Sir John Simon, the Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs, was sharply criticized in various quarters for his cool <b>acceptance</b> <b>of</b> a gross <b>breach</b> <b>of</b> the Covenant. Inaction, while avoiding danger at the moment, was bound to increase the perils of the future by encouraging aggression elsewhere. Thus, Sino-Japanise crisis of 1931 - 33, in the sequence of events which culminated in the Second World War, provides effective illustrations of British "appeasement policy" of the interwar period...|$|R
