50|$|In medieval Europe, an oath of fealty (German: Lehnseid) was a {{fundamental}} {{element of the}} feudal system in the Holy Roman Empire. It was sworn between two people, the obliged person (vassal) and a person of rank (liege lord). The oath of allegiance was usually carried out {{as part of a}} traditional ceremony in which the liegeman or vassal gave his lord a pledge <b>of</b> loyalty and <b>acceptance</b> <b>of</b> the consequences <b>of</b> a <b>breach</b> <b>of</b> trust. In return the liege lord promised to protect and remain loyal to his vassal. The rights conferred on the vassal were so similar to actual possession that it was described as beneficial ownership (dominium utile), whereas the rights of the lord were referred to as direct ownership (dominium directum).|$|R
